Hi, 

**Request**
Would it be doable to add a new error message when someone tries to respond to a WebSocket like it's a normal HTTP request?

**Reason**
WebSockets are not supported by express, but their original handshake request is a normal HTTP request. Because of this, it is possible to make a mistake where you try to send data to this request.

These are two scenarios where this may happen:
```js
router.get('*', function(req, res) {
  res.status(404).send('Page not found');
});

app.use(function (err, req, res) {
    log.error('Error on path %s\n%s\n', req.url, err.stack);
    res.status(500).send( 'Internal Server Error');
}); 
```
This wil currently give you a vague error like this:
```
TypeError: Cannot read property 'length' of null
    at ServerResponse.OutgoingMessage._send (_http_outgoing.js:138:38)
    at ServerResponse.OutgoingMessage.write (_http_outgoing.js:492:16)
    at ServerResponse.OutgoingMessage.end (_http_outgoing.js:589:10)
    at writeend (/home/...../my_app/node_modules/express-session/index.js:261:22)
    at Immediate.onsave (/home/...../my_app/node_modules/express-session/index.js:335:11)
    at runCallback (timers.js:666:20)
    at tryOnImmediate (timers.js:639:5)
    at processImmediate [as _immediateCallback] (timers.js:611:5)
```

**Possible solution**
Adding the following code at`response.js:214` in the `res.send` function should handle this case, though there may be more elegant solutions.
```js
if (req.upgrade === 'websocket') {
  throw new Error('Sending data to websockets is not supported')
}

```

